ညးကလေင်အာမံင် ပ္ဍဲဍုင်ဗၟာတုဲ ညးပံင် ကုညးတၠသိက္ခာ ဒရ်ရောရ်
Dr. Halliday later came back to Burma and was designated to educational work in Moulmein the capital of Mon State where for several years he was co-labor of Rev. A.C. Darrow, then in charge of the evangelistic work of the station. Being a master of the Mon language, Dr. Halliday was able to render valuable aid to Dr. C. O. Blagden, Mon epigraphist, in the translation of the Myazedi inscription of Pagan, the Rosetta Stone for the ancient Mon and the lost of Pyu languages, which service was especially acknowledged by Dr. Blagden in his published paper on this subject. Dr. Halliday also collaborated with Dr. Blagden in editing the Mon inscription of Siam. His greatest contribution to education in Burma was through valuable articles written for the Journal of the Burma Research Society, the editing of Mon texts for the Government, and the publication of an annotated translation of the History Mon Kings. His monograph on the Mons made at the request of the Government in connection with its ethnological survey, was an outstanding piece of work.
In various ways, sholars and officials have given high praise to Dr. Halliday’s tireless research work in Mon. It was in recognition of his great service to the Government and to literature that Dr. Halliday was awarded the Kaisar-I-Hind gold medal in January 1930, and in recognition of his scholarship he was given the degree of Doctor of Literature by the University of Rangoon in July 1932. How he ever found time to do so much, no one could understand for no immediate duty or task was ever slighted and for years he carried heavy responsibilities in mission work. All who knew his work, felt that no honor had ever been more truly deserved or fully earned; and one could add that few personalities could grace an honor with such simple dignity as was his. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/006293246
 |title=Digital Library |last= |first= |date=06.12.2019 |website=hathitrust.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://trove.nla.gov.au/people/1080539?q=creator%3A%22Halliday%2C+Robert%2C+1864-1933.%22&c=people|title=Halliday, Robert (1864-1933)|last= |first= |date=06.12.2019 |website=trove.nla.gov.au |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>


Dr. Halliday will never be forgotten by the Mon people, whom he loved and who love him. The Mon people owe a debt of gratitude to Dr. Halliday, a very special foreigner who leaves to them a very rich legacy.



On July 1, 1933, occurred the death of Rev. Robert Hallliday Litt.D., of Moulmein Burma.

